flowRoot.flowPara: Anna is participating to a hackaton about smartcities. She joins a team of enthousiasts and gets debriefed about the hackaton. It lasts the weekend (2d) and Sunday evening is demo day. The topic is broad, as long as it is smartcities.

After forming a team, Anna and team need to decide what problem they will solve. Mikko, a developer part of the team remembers an API catalog called apinf.io and suggests to browse the APIs available there to get some inspiration.
They navigate to apinf.io and find the smartcities tag, which lists all APIs that are connected to smartcities.
Have some fun and learn new things. Get to know some people.
Typically you run out of time during a hackaton. You make fast decisions and build something very rough.
Short on time. Working with people you don't know.
API card and detail view give a good overview of the API itself
Get inspiration to come up with a problem worth solving with the APIs available.
Are there any APIs that can help us solve a problem in the smartcities category?
There are a lot of possible tags to filter on. Taxonomy is hard, but users should not get lost.
Exploring mode. A bit curious to learn about a platform recommended by a team member.
Excited!
The team browses through the APIs in the catalog. There is a lot of APIs about traffic, trash, sensors (air quality)
The team decides to build an app that learns about the users daily travelling routines and will give suggestions in order to avoid traffic jams in the future.
They need to decide which traffic API they will use first to build their prototype.

First the team checks the API from their hometown, Tampere. It's not really well documented (which they flag) so they decided to look for another one. Surprisingly the city of Oulu has a very good traffic API, but after glancing at the data they notice that there aren't a lot of traffic jams... Finally they settle on Helsinki traffic API.

After playing with the "try out" functionality in the API, they decide to generate an SDK to get started with the app. They chose the technology they want to develop in and get a headstart with the generated code. Time saver!

Thanks to clear documentation of the API and the SDK generated, it does not take too much time to get a first prototype running that fetches the correct data. This way, they can focus on the other parts of the app (logic,...).
Sometimes the API is not optimal for their use case, which they quickly create tickets for in the feedback section for the API.
The team manages to get a first prototype up and running the first day, which allows them to get feedback the second day and finetune.
Obviously they win the competition.
They decided from the start to opensource the project and add attributions to apinf.io on their Github page.
Learns a bit about smartcities and that it is an actual very broad topic.

text.tspan: GOALS: Win a hackaton about smartcities

flowRoot.flowPara: Later on, the team gets contacted by the city of Turku and asked if they want to integrate their data API - for a small fee.
The team goes back to apinf.io and checks how the data looks like. Luckily mashups are easy to accomplish with apinf.io, so integrating the dataset is very easy.
APIs have multiple groupings. Traffic APIs also have e.g. smartcities tag.
You can understand what the API is about and what data is provides in the blink of an eye.
